		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="bfont"> From: neal</font><BR><font class="bfont"><A HREF='/lotr/resources/buzz.php'>Back to Topics List</A></font><TABLE WIDTH=100% border="0" cellpadding="6"><tr><TD ALIGN='LEFT' valign='top' width='70' bgcolor=#A2B1C1><font class="h2font"> Name</td><TD ALIGN='LEFT' valign='top' bgcolor=#A2B1C1><font class="h2font"> Comment</td></tr><TR><TD ALIGN='LEFT' valign='top' width='70' bgcolor=#FFFFFF><font class="bfont"><B>Ghetto 13</B></font></td><Td valign='top' bgcolor=#FFFFFF><font class="bfont">Best players I&#39;ve seen play: Clint Hays, Bastian Winklehaus, Hayes Hunter.  These guys just win, no matter what they&#39;re playing against or what else is going on.<br>
<br>
Best player you&#39;ve never seen play: Jonathan Plante.  If he&#39;d ever get a real job and make it to a Con, he upset a few "better known" players.  The guy has what the three above do, the ability to pull a game out from almost any situation.<br>
<br>
Most Over-rated Player I&#39;ve ever seen: John Lolli.  He&#39;s my boy, and you can&#39;t take anything away from somebody who won $2,500.  But A) a large piece of winning Origins was scouting ahead, which is shunned in just about every other game but this one, and B) I&#39;ve seen him repeatedly lose games to newbies, make silly plays, etc. </TD></TR><TR><TD ALIGN='LEFT' valign='top' width='70' bgcolor=#A2B1C1><font class="bfont"><B>SeaRaptor</B></font></td><Td valign='top' bgcolor=#A2B1C1><font class="bfont">This is why I love Trust Me and Hobbits when compared to the ultra-boring Men/Elves deck that pretty much plays itself.  Blech.   </TD></TR><TR><TD ALIGN='LEFT' valign='top' width='70' bgcolor=#FFFFFF><font class="bfont"><B>The Judge</B></font></td><Td valign='top' bgcolor=#FFFFFF><font class="bfont">Thats when it gets a little tricky in this game is thinking ahead..how many times you can do this or that...Trust Me deck actually require some thinking as do Hobbit decks.<br>
