<br>
I&#39;ll give a recap just because this was about the most insane game I&#39;ve ever had.  Our rider was holding a box tournament, it was the final round, I was playing against John Lolli, who was the only undefeated at that point.  So if John won, he got the box, and if I won, it&#39;d prolly go to one of the other 4-1&#39;s, because I had a bye.<br>
<br>
John, as usual, is playing some completely off-the-wall deck, and I have Hobbits.  He knows what I&#39;m playing by then, and bids 9 to go first, to my standard 7.  We both get to site 3 (after he decides not to give me enough pool to play my Troll at 2), but he Hates my exhausted Sam at site 2, so I&#39;m stuck with 3 burdens and he&#39;s got Enduring Evils.  He stops at site 4, saying that if I can double the entire way against him, then I&#39;m a champ.  I double to 5 living off my Stealths and Filibert, but left with only Frodo.  He moves to 5, and I have a Scrabbler and 2x Threat of the Unknown in my hand.  So I figure I can Scrabbler, Balrog, then like a Keyward or something to draw a bunch of cards with the Threat.  But, [MISTAKE #1] I forgot that Balrog got discarded to Proudfoot, so I got just a Scabbler and all those cards are useless.  So he gets to 6 pretty easily.  I drop Aragorn and Legolas, then head to (my) Caras Galadon.  He drops 4 big beefy Orcs, and I need to double here, so [MISTAKE #2] I exert Aragorn 3 times to make him Defender +3.  And as John is more than happy to point out to me, that does jack at Caras Galadon.  So Aragorn dies because he was dumb, Legolas dies to an Enduring Evil, and Orophin dies because he has nothing better to do.  I&#39;m left with lone Frodo once again, against like 45 str worth of Orcs.  I&#39;m have balls of steel, so I move on, but I find a completely unexpected Confluence, which thouroughly screws me.  He plays an Enquea to supplement his Orcs, and I play 3x PATHS so everybody but Enquea dies, and I take 2 wounds.  He moves to 7 and stops.  Frodo heads to 8, still all alone to his Shores (more on this later), and finds Toldea and Enquea.  While I&#39;ve got 6 burdens, those two do nothing while I&#39;ve got only Frodo. :-)  Anyway, I ditch There and Back Again, Bounder the first fight, and play a Stealth for the second fight, so I take 2 wounds.  [MISTAKE #3]  Anyway, I completely neglect that I could stop him because he was for some reason playing Shores, but anyway I feel Confident because I&#39;ve got Elbereth and I&#39;m moving against Nazgul.  However, I&#39;m obviously a bad player, so while I can cancel the skirmish against 20 million orcs the first time with Elbereth, when Toldea and Enquea come back for more, without Elbereth one Intuition and one Stealth don&#39;t prevent Frodo from getting overwhelmed.  So I lose.  And then I realized that moving to 9 with that setup, I made it impossible for me to win.<br>
<br>
Now, if I weren&#39;t a bad player, what would I have done?  Stopped?  Heck no, because there likely wouldn&#39;t be any Nazgul around at site 9, even if I did stop him.  Let&#39;s recreate the scenario though.  I&#39;ve got Frodo, Hobbit Sword, Elbereth, Mithril Coat, There and Back Again, and Bounder out, and 2x Intuition and 1x Stealth (and 1x PATHS that didn&#39;t matter).  Fighting Toldea and Enquea at 8.  Here&#39;s what I did:<br>
<br>
TABA, Bounder, Take a Wound, Intuition, Take a Wound, Move, ditch Elbereth, Intuition, Stealth, get overwhelmed.<br>
<br>
Here&#39;s what I should have done:<br>
<br>
TABA, Intuition, Take a Wound, Intuition, Take a Wound, Move, ditch Elbereth, Steath, Bounder, Take a Wound.<br>
<br>
See what I mean about needing to plan mad stuff in advance?<br>
<br>
But in any case, John told me he had a Tower Assassin in hand at site 9, so I would&#39;ve died regardless without the Bounder. :-) </TD></TR><TR><TD ALIGN='LEFT' valign='top' width='70' bgcolor=#A2B1C1><font class="bfont"><B>The Judge</B></font></td><Td valign='top' bgcolor=#A2B1C1><font class="bfont">Doug, thats hilarious dude.<br>
